research/history/round_summaries/round_0179.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `lowrank_jumprelu_residual` under the unchanged mainline recipe (`K=128, EF=2, signum, lr=3.0e-3`). Final reconstruction is `x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i`, where `U(Vx)` is a static low-rank trunk and the JumpReLU selector only changes which residual dictionary atoms `b_i` are activated and their coefficients. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`: LUTurbo/Lottable can export the trunk factors and residual dictionary as static vector libraries, then execute `trunk lookup + thresholded sparse selection + weighted lookup-sum` online. The probe asks one question only: in the low-EF feasible regime, does learned thresholding provide a better architecture tradeoff than the current soft-codebook two-stage mainline, or should this family be ruled out. Encoder selection cost should stay in the feasible band at `EF=2`, so this should produce a real signal instead of a policy reject.",
